SIMPLE: neck
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Neck
<hw>Neck</hw> <pr>(n⟦ecr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>necke</ets>, AS. <ets>hnecca</ets>; akin to D. <ets>nek</ets> the
nape of the neck, G. <ets>nacken</ets>, OHG. <ets>nacch</ets>,
<ets>hnacch</ets>, Icel. <ets>hnakki</ets>, Sw. <ets>nacke</ets>, Dan.
<ets>nakke</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The part of an animal which
connects the head and the trunk, and which, in man and many other
animals, is more slender than the trunk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any part of an inanimate object corresponding to or
resembling the neck of an animal</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The long
slender part of a vessel, as a retort, or of a fruit, as a gourd.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A long narrow tract of land projecting from the main
body, or a narrow tract connecting two larger tracts.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>That part of a violin, guitar, or similar
instrument, which extends from the head to the body, and on which is the
finger board or fret board.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A reduction in size near the end
of an object, formed by a groove around it; <as>as, a <ex>neck</ex>
forming the journal of a shaft</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>the point where the base of the
stem of a plant arises from the root.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Neck and crop</b></col>, <cd>completely; wholly;
altogether; roughly and at once.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> --
<col><b>Neck and neck</b></col> <fld>(Racing)</fld>, <cd>so nearly equal
that one cannot be said to be before the other; very close; even; side
by side.</cd> -- <col><b>Neck of a capital</b></col>. <fld>(Arch.)</fld>
<cd>See <er>Gorgerin</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Neck of a cascabel</b></col>
<fld>(Gun.)</fld>, <cd>the part joining the knob to the base of the
breech.</cd> -- <col><b>Neck of a gun</b></col>, <cd>the small part of
the piece between the chase and the swell of the muzzle.</cd> --
<col><b>Neck of a tooth</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the
constriction between the root and the crown.</cd> -- <col><b>Neck or
nothing</b></col> <mark>(Fig.)</mark>, <cd>at all risks.</cd> --
<col><b>Neck verse</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The verse formerly read
to entitle a party to the benefit of clergy, said to be the first verse
of the fifty-first Psalm, ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Miserere mei</xex>,⟦rdquo⟧
etc.</cd> <au>Sir W. Scott.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <specif>Hence,</specif>
<cd>a verse or saying, the utterance of which decides one's fate; a
shibboleth.</cd>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<q>These words, ⟦ldquo⟧bread and cheese,⟦rdquo⟧ were their <qex>neck
verse</qex> or shibboleth to distinguish them; all pronouncing
⟦ldquo⟧broad and cause,⟦rdquo⟧ being presently put to death.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
-- <col><b>Neck yoke</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A bar by which the end
of the tongue of a wagon or carriage is suspended from the collars of
the harnesses.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A device with projecting arms for
carrying things (as buckets of water or sap) suspended from one's
shoulders.</cd> -- <col><b>On the neck of</b></col>, <cd>immediately
after; following closely; on the heel of.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Committing one sin
<xex>on the neck of</xex> another.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>W. Perkins.</au> --
<col><b>Stiff neck</b></col>, <cd>obstinacy in evil or wrong; inflexible
obstinacy; contumacy.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I know thy rebellion, and thy
<xex>stiff neck</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Deut. xxxi. 27.</au> -- <col><b>To
break the neck of</b></col>, <cd>to destroy the main force of; to break
the back of.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧What they presume to borrow from her sage and
virtuous rules . . . <xex>breaks the neck of</xex> their own
cause.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au> -- <col><b>To harden the neck</b></col>,
<cd>to grow obstinate; to be more and more perverse and rebellious.</cd>
<au>Neh. ix. 17.</au> -- <col><b>To tread on the neck of</b></col>,
<cd>to oppress; to tyrannize over.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Neck
<hw>Neck</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Necked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Necking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>To reduce the
diameter of (an object) near its end, by making a groove around it; --
used with <ptcl>down</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>neck</ex> down a
shaft</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>neck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: neck
<hw>neck</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To kiss and caress amorously.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <wordforms><pos>n.</pos>
<wf>necking</wf>.</wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neckar nut</ent>⟦br⟧
